# Kingsight API — Project Overview

ASP.NET Core 8 Web API (`kingsightapi`) that exposes read/update endpoints for mortgage dimension data in Microsoft Fabric, consumed by an Angular frontend.

## Structure

| Folder | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `Controllers/` | Thin HTTP layer — validation, status codes, logging |
| `Services/` | Business logic, raw SQL, `I*Service` interfaces + `sealed` implementations |
| `Entities/` | DTOs, request/response models (no EF entities) |
| `Program.cs` | DI, CORS, Swagger, JSON options |

## Stack

- .NET 8, nullable enabled, implicit usings
- `Microsoft.Data.SqlClient` against Fabric (`FabricConnectionString` in config)
- Swashbuckle for OpenAPI in Development
- No ORM — parameterized SQL only

## Schemas

- `mort.dim_loan`, `mort.dim_investor` — loan and investor dimensions
- `wh_enterprise_gold.dbo.dim_fund` — fund dimension

Filter current rows with `is_current = 1` where applicable.

## DI & lifetime

Register services as **Singleton** in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IInvestorService, InvestorService>();
```

Match existing registrations when adding new services.

## JSON & Angular

- Serialize responses with **camelCase** (`PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.CamelCase`)
- Accept camelCase request bodies (`PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true`)
- CORS policy `AllowAngularDev` allows `http://localhost:4200`

Support plural route aliases when Angular uses them (e.g. `alias` and `aliases` on investor updates).

## Security

- Never commit connection strings or secrets in `appsettings.json`; use User Secrets locally and secure config in deployed environments
- Do not log passwords or full connection strings

## Comments & readability (project-wide)

Code should be understandable without reading every line. Prefer clear names first; add comments only where they add context names cannot carry.

| Layer | Comment style |
|-------|----------------|
| `Controllers/` | `// GET: api/...` above each action; brief notes for non-obvious routes (Angular aliases, status codes) |
| `Services/` | One-line summary above SQL constants; section headers for complex methods |
| `Entities/` | `/// <summary>` on public DTOs and non-obvious properties |
| `Program.cs` | Section comments for DI, CORS, JSON, pipeline blocks |

**Do**

- Explain *why* (business rule, Angular contract, Fabric filter such as `is_current = 1`)
- Keep comments up to date when behavior changes
- Use full sentences for multi-line or XML summaries

**Do not**

- Restate obvious code (`// increment i`, `// return Ok`)
- Leave large blocks of commented-out code — delete or ask before restoring
- Use comments instead of renaming unclear variables or methods

## Scope of changes

- Keep diffs minimal and localized to the requested feature
- Reuse existing service/controller patterns before introducing new abstractions
- Do not modify `FundServiceOld.cs` or commented legacy code unless explicitly asked
- When adding features, include comments per the table above so new code matches existing readability
